<p>
<seg id=1> Tang Jiaxuan, foreign minister for China, and Madeleine Albright, United States secretary of state, jointly held a press conference in Washington on the 29th in which they spoke about U.S.-China relations. Tang is currently on a visit to the United States. </seg>
<seg id=2> Tang Jiaxuan spoke of President Clinton's scandal as being a domestic matter, that China would never forget President Clinton's contribution to friendly relations between the two countries. </seg>
<seg id=3> Voice of America's Zhou Youkang filed the following report from the press conference. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Hello radio listeners: President Clinton met with Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, in Washington for a visit at the White House at 11:30 am on the 29th. Tang is in Washington for a visit. </seg>
<seg id=5> Secretary of State Albright held a joint press conference with Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan at the Department of State at noon on the 29th to announce the news that President Clinton had met with Tang Jiaxuan. </seg>
<seg id=6> Albright said: </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Secretary of State Albright said, I'm very happy to tell everyone that Foreign Minister Tang and President Clinton just had a meeting, and to announce that China has decided to sign the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights on October 5 in New York. </seg>
<seg id=8> Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan said during the press conference that it was of great significance to meet with President Clinton. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> I believe my meeting with President Clinton was a successful one. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> President Clinton is currently in the midst of an eventful period. Due to the scandal surrounding him, many people in the United States have been extremely dissatisfied and critical of him. </seg>
<seg id=11> Some have suggested that he should be impeached, others have said that he should voluntarily step down from office, while some Democratic congresspersons have even distanced themselves from the president. </seg>
<seg id=12> However, Chinese foreign minister Tang Jiaxuan did not see the subject as taboo, generously praising and commending President Clinton for his contribution to the promotion of U.S.-China relations. </seg>
<seg id=13> During the press conference a reporter asked Tang Jiaxuan whether Clinton's scandal would affect relations between the two countries. </seg>
<seg id=14> Tang Jiaxuan said: </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=15> I think that this is completely an internal matter for the United States. </seg>
<seg id=16> I have never believed that this would have an effect upon the development of relations with China. </seg>
<seg id=17> President Clinton himself has made an invaluably important contribution to the development of U.S.-China relations, we will never forget what he has done. </seg>
<seg id=18> As for me, a person from China, I sincerely hope for the actual and stable continuation of the advancement of U.S.-China relations that will be happen  based upon the three joint communiques as well as the joint statements by leaders from both countries. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=19> Chinese communist officials have repeatedly said that Taiwan is a province of China, and that the issue of Taiwan is an internal one. </seg>
<seg id=20> Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan repeatedly spoke of the Taiwan issue both in the United Nations General Assembly and in multiple public forums during his visit to Washington. </seg>
<seg id=21> During a press conference, when asked by a reporter what the greatest obstacle was to the U.S. and China becoming strategic partners was, Tang Jiaxuan said: </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=22> I think we've spoken of this many times already. In terms of this we especially need to take care to use appropriate measures in handling the issue of Taiwan. </seg>
<seg id=23> Taiwan is the most sensitive issue in U.S.-China relations, and it is also the most immediate one. </seg>
</p>
